<emphasis id="77E4EA9A2B654909FF22655752D1FA6C" bold="true" box="[238,401,1400,1427]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Chrysotoxum</emphasis>
Meigen
</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="452F36882B654909FF5B65EF5282F970" blockId="14.[151,1437,1472,1679]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
The genus 
<taxonomicName id="82904D0B2B654909FEDF65EF52E8FA25" box="[275,424,1472,1498]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Chrysotoxum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="77E4EA9A2B654909FEDF65EF52E8FA25" box="[275,424,1472,1498]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Chrysotoxum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
comprises large, wasp-mimicking species (
<bibRefCitation id="21014B792B654909FC5F65EE5701FA24" author="van Veen, M. P." box="[915,1089,1473,1499]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" refId="ref41487" refString="van Veen, M. P. (2004) Hoverflies of Northwest Europe. KNNV Publishing, Utrecht, 254 pp. https: // doi. org / 10.1163 / 9789004274495" type="book" year="2004">
van 
<collectingRegion id="8754F86A2B654909FC0865EE50BCFA24" box="[964,1020,1473,1499]" country="Austria" name="Wien" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Veen</collectingRegion>
2004
</bibRefCitation>
). Species of the genus 
<taxonomicName id="82904D0B2B654909FA8E65EF539BFA01" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Chrysotoxum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="77E4EA9A2B654909FA8E65EF539BFA01" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Chrysotoxum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are widely distributed in all zoogeographical regions except Australasian and the Antarctic with approximately 150 species mostly in the Palaearctic region (
<bibRefCitation id="21014B792B654909FD216627509BF9DC" author="Evenhuis, N. L. &amp; Pape, T. &amp; Pont, A. C. &amp; Thompson, F. C." box="[749,987,1544,1571]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" refId="ref35348" refString="Evenhuis, N. L., Pape, T., Pont, A. C. &amp; Thompson, F. C. (2008) Biosystematic Database of World Diptera, Version 10. 5. Available from: http: // www. sel. barc. usda. gov / diptera / biosys. htm (accessed 25 February 2013)" type="url" year="2008">
Evenhuis 
<emphasis id="77E4EA9A2B654909FC93662650D1F9DD" box="[863,913,1544,1570]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">et al</emphasis>
. 2008
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="21014B792B654909FC2B662757A5F9DC" author="Thompson, F. C. &amp; Rotheray, G. E. &amp; Zumbado, M. A." box="[999,1253,1544,1571]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" refId="ref41174" refString="Thompson, F. C., Rotheray, G. E. &amp; Zumbado, M. A. (2010) Syrphidae (Flower flies). In: Brown, B. V., Borkent, A., Cumming, J. M., Wood, D. M., Woodley, N. E. &amp; Zumbado, M. A. (Eds.), Manual of Central American Diptera. Vol. 2. NRC Research Press, Ottawa, pp. 763 - 792." type="book" year="2010">
Thompson 
<emphasis id="77E4EA9A2B654909FBAB662657DAF9DD" box="[1127,1178,1544,1570]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">et al</emphasis>
. 2010
</bibRefCitation>
). The adult flies of European 
<taxonomicName id="82904D0B2B654909FEEB660352FCF9B9" box="[295,444,1580,1606]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Chrysotoxum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="77E4EA9A2B654909FEEB660352FCF9B9" box="[295,444,1580,1606]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Chrysotoxum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species can be found in deciduous and coniferous forests and grasslands (
<bibRefCitation id="21014B792B654909FB3A660356D1F9B8" author="Speight, M. C. D." box="[1270,1425,1580,1607]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" refId="ref40366" refString="Speight, M. C. D. (2020) Species accounts of European Syrphidae (Diptera), 2020. Syrph the Net, the database of European Syrphidae (Diptera). Vol. 104. Syrph the Net publications, Dublin, 313 pp." type="book" year="2020">Speight 2020</bibRefCitation>
). Larvae are specialized in preying upon root aphids associated with ant nests (
<bibRefCitation id="21014B792B654909FC22667F5648F994" author="Rotheray, G. E. &amp; Gilbert, F." box="[1006,1288,1616,1643]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" refId="ref39858" refString="Rotheray, G. E. &amp; Gilbert, F. (2011) The Natural History of Hoverflies. The Blissett Group, London, xiv + 334 pp." type="book" year="2011">Rotheray &amp; Gilbert 2011</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="21014B792B654909FADF667F5251F970" author="Nedeljkovic, Z. &amp; Acanski, J. &amp; Vujic, A. &amp; Obreht, D. &amp; Dan, M. &amp; Stahls, G &amp; Radenkovic, S." pageId="14" pageNumber="15" pagination="84 - 102" refId="ref38303" refString="Nedeljkovic, Z., Acanski, J., Vujic, A., Obreht, D., Dan, M., Stahls, G &amp; Radenkovic, S. (2013) Taxonomy of Chrysotoxum festivum Linnaeus, 1758 (Diptera: Syrphidae) - an integrative approach. Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society, 169, 84 - 102. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / zoj. 12052" type="journal article" year="2013">
Nedeljkovic 
<emphasis id="77E4EA9A2B654909FF5B665A5388F971" box="[151,200,1652,1678]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">et al</emphasis>
. 2013
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="21014B792B654909FED1665B52F7F970" author="Speight, M. C. D." box="[285,439,1652,1679]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" refId="ref40366" refString="Speight, M. C. D. (2020) Species accounts of European Syrphidae (Diptera), 2020. Syrph the Net, the database of European Syrphidae (Diptera). Vol. 104. Syrph the Net publications, Dublin, 313 pp." type="book" year="2020">Speight 2020</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
